  "prompt": "Can a minor sue or be sued?",
  "response": "Yes, a minor (a person under the age of 18 in most jurisdictions) can sue or be sued, but the process involves specific legal considerations and protections due to their status as a minor.\n\n### **Suing as a Minor:**\n1. **Representation by a Guardian or Next Friend:** Minors typically cannot file lawsuits on their own. Instead, they must sue through a **guardian ad litem** or a \"next friend\" (usually a parent or legal guardian) who acts on their behalf.\n2. **Court Approval:** Settlements or judgments involving minors often require court approval to ensure the minor\u2019s interests are protected.\n3. **Statute of Limitations:** In some cases, the statute of limitations for filing a lawsuit may be **tolled** (paused) until the minor reaches the age of majority, giving them additional time to file a claim.\n\n### **Being Sued as a Minor:**\n1. **Liability:** Minors can be held legally responsible for their actions, such as in cases of negligence, contract disputes (in limited circumstances), or intentional torts.\n2. **Parental Liability:** In some cases, parents or guardians may be held financially liable for the minor\u2019s actions, depending on local laws.\n3. **Court-Appointed Representation:** If a minor is sued, they may need a guardian ad litem or legal representative to defend their interests.\n4. **Enforcement of Judgments:** While a minor can be sued, enforcing a judgment against them may be more complex. Courts may require the judgment to be enforced only after the minor reaches adulthood.\n\n### **Key Considerations:**\n- The laws regarding minors and legal actions vary by jurisdiction, so specific rules may differ depending on where you live.\n- Minors are often afforded additional protections in legal proceedings to ensure their rights are safeguarded.\n\nIf you\u2019re dealing with a legal issue involving a minor, it\u2019s advisable to consult a qualified attorney to navigate the complexities of such cases.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
